| Limited opportunities           | Restriction of access to education, employment, and social participation                     | Social Work Institute, 2024                                                            |

## Conclusion

The negative consequences of stereotyping are multifaceted, impacting individuals’ psychological well-being, academic and professional performance, and broader social structures. Stereotypes not only cause immediate emotional distress and cognitive impairments but also contribute to long-term disengagement and systemic inequalities. The reinforcement of cultural divisions further exacerbates social fragmentation, reducing cohesion and productivity in various contexts.

Given the substantial evidence of harm, it is imperative for researchers, policymakers, educators, and social workers to continue developing and implementing interventions that mitigate the effects of stereotyping. These efforts should focus on education, awareness, and structural changes to promote inclusivity and equity.

